solution.p:
Write f(x)=e^x. Since f(x) is continuous and differentiable, the Mean Value Theorem asserts that
there exists some c between 0 and T such that


f'(c)&=\frac{f(T)-f(0)}{T-0}

The problem asks us to find this value of c. Solving:
 e^c&=\frac{e^T-e^0}{T}

e^c&=\frac{e^T-1}{T}

 c&=\log\left(\frac{e^T-1}{T}\right)

In order to find C_+, we find f(1), because we know angles for which the secant and cosecant are x=1.
\cos(0)\amp=1 \amp\amp\implies \amp\sec(0)\amp=\tfrac{1}{1}=1 \amp\amp\implies \amp\amp\arcsec(1)=0
\sin\big(\tfrac{\pi}{2}\big)\amp=1 \amp\amp\implies \amp\csc\big(\tfrac{\pi}{2}\big)\amp=\tfrac{1}{1}=1 \amp\amp\implies \amp\amp\arccsc(1)=\tfrac{\pi}{2}
So
C_+=\arcsec(1)+\arccsc(1)=\tfrac{\pi}{2}
In order to find C_-, we find f(-1), because we know angles for which the secant and cosecant are x=-1.
\cos(\pi)\amp=-1 \amp\amp\implies \amp\sec(\pi)\amp=\tfrac{1}{-1}=-1 \amp\amp\implies \amp\amp\arcsec(-1)=\pi
\sin\big(-\tfrac{\pi}{2}\big)\amp=-1 \amp\amp\implies \amp\csc\big(-\tfrac{\pi}{2}\big)\amp=\tfrac{1}{-1}=-1 \amp\amp\implies \amp\amp\arccsc(-1)=-\tfrac{\pi}{2}
So
C_-=\arcsec(-1)+\arccsc(-1)=\tfrac{\pi}{2}
This shows that f(x)=\arcsec x + \arccsc x=\frac{\pi}{2} for all |x|\ge 1 and \arcsec x = \frac{\pi}{2}- \arccsc x for all |x|\ge 1.

